Copper(I) iodide can be found in three forms (Keen, 1995): \begin{itemize} \item $\alpha$-CuI is stable above 673$\pm$8K, and is in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB8_cF36_225_a_f-001}{$\delta$-Bi$_{2}$O$_{3}$ structure}, with the iodine atoms on the (2a) Wyckoff positions and the copper atoms occupying 1/8 of the (32f) positions. \item $\gamma$-CuI (marshite) is the ground state, stable below $643 \pm 2$K, and is also in the $\delta$-Bi$_{2}$O$_{3}$ structure. \item In the intermediate temperature range $\beta$-CuI is generally agreed to be trigonal or hexagonal, but the exact structure is under dispute: \begin{itemize} \item (Kurdyumova, 1961) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_hP12_156_3a2bc_3a2bc-001}{trigonal space group $P3m1$ \#156}.  Their unit cell, which is three times larger than the standard cell for this structure and is now considered erroneous, is the one listed on this page. (Abrahams, 2008). \item (B\"{u}hrer, 1977) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B_hP6_187_gi_ad-001}{hexagonal space group $P\overline{6}m2$ \#187}, with the copper atoms partially occupying two sites. \item (Sakuma, 1988) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_hP4_156_ab_ab-001}{trigonal space group $P3m1$ \#156} with a smaller unit cell than (Kurdyumova, 1961) and no disorder on the copper sites. \item (Keen, 1994) placed it in \href{current_web_home_dir/A2B_hP6_164_2d_d-001}{trigonal space group $P\overline{3}m1$ \#164}, with a unit cell similar to (B\"{u}hrer, 1977) and (Sakuma, 1988).  Like the former paper, the oxygen positions are disordered. \end{itemize} \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 Space group $P3m1$ \#156 allows an arbitary choice of origin for the $z$-axis.  Used this freedom to place the I-III atom at the origin. 
 This structure originally appeared in (Hicks, 2019).  This page has been rewritten, but the structure itself has not changed.
